      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "6fbd5c46358188d1",
      "text": "The distinctions that become actionable and order the mix in the course of a conflict can vary depending on the nature of the conflict. However, here are some common distinctions that may emerge and ultimately lead to opposing parties fighting each other:\n\nIdeological differences: Conflicts can arise when groups or individuals have different ideological beliefs, such as different views on the role of government, religion, or social values. These differences can lead to opposing parties fighting for their respective ideologies or beliefs.\n\nResource competition: Conflicts can arise when different groups or individuals are competing for the same resources, such as land, water, or energy. This can lead to opposing parties fighting for control of those resources.\n\nIdentity differences: Conflicts can arise when groups or individuals have different cultural, ethnic, or national identities. This can lead to opposing parties fighting for recognition or protection of their respective identities.\n\nPower struggles: Conflicts can arise when different groups or individuals are vying for power, control, or influence. This can lead to opposing parties fighting for political or economic dominance.\n\nHistorical grievances: Conflicts can arise when groups or individuals have long-standing historical grievances, such as past injustices or conflicts. This can lead to opposing parties fighting to seek redress for those past grievances.\n\nUltimately, the distinctions that become actionable and order the mix in the course of a conflict depend on the specific context of the conflict. However, it is important to note that conflicts often involve complex and interconnected factors, and a nuanced understanding of the underlying issues is crucial for finding effective solutions and achieving lasting peace.\n\n\n"
